{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":495,"record_hash":"sha256:097275cc302c960889403307bcee59f84116ab091d3da75e5ff52a593943f840","timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:13:24.342Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 2e84e7\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3820\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of a\ncapture turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A capture turn layer would preserve that missing context without\nforcing us to immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit,\nchange, or pull request.\n\n## V1 Contract\n\nImplement v1 around persisted capture observations, derived indexes, and\nread-time association. Do not persist inferred ownership.\n\nPersisted hierarchy:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session\n    capture turns\n      transcript records\n```\n\nStorage shape:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n```\n\nCore rules:\n\n- A capture turn is created only when capture accepts at least one new\n  transcript record.\n- `TurnDetail.records` is an ordered array and is authoritative for rendering\n  order within the capture turn.\n- Backfilled capture turns may contain many logical conversation/provider turns,\n  so records must carry provider/display grouping metadata when available.\n- `turn_key` is `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`, computed from UTF-8 stored\n  `session_key`, `s\n[TRUNCATED]\n, allowing typed metadata replacement inside the existing\natomic `apply_edits` path. The `but-agentlog` implementation should bump the\npinned `git-meta-lib` dependency to a revision containing that change, then use\none `apply_edits` call for transcript appends, record hash updates, turn detail\nwrites, turn summary appends, and index updates.\nThe capture path should not use plain `set`, `set_record`, or similar\nout-of-band writes for session/source metadata once turn writes are introduced.\n\n## Environment Snapshot\n\nEach turn should capture the repository state that can help later association.\nTranscript capture is the primary operation. Environment snapshot collection is\nbest-effort: if transcript records are accepted but environment collection\nfails, still write the turn and store a failed snapshot status instead of\nfailing the whole capture.\n\nCandidate fields:\n\n- uncommitted worktree files: all tracked and untracked files with uncommitted\n  changes\n- stacks: zero, one, or many\n- branches in each stack\n- optional review unit for each branch, for example a pull request\n- commits in each branch\n- optional change id for each commit\n- files changed by each commit\n\nAlso store a compact `observed_targets` summary on the turn detail. It should\ncontain the canonical branch, review, and change keys that were indexed for this\nturn. This keeps candidate verification and future index rebuilds cheap without\nduplicating the whole environment snapshot in every reader.\n`observed_targets` is a deterministic projection of `environment`, not a second\nsource of truth. Writers derive it from the same snapshot in the same atomic\nwrite. Readers may verify index hits against it before reading the heavier\nenvironment detail.\n\nPlain Git mode should use the same snapshot path as GitButler mode. The\nexpectation is that the GitButler workspace/head-info APIs expose a compatible\nstack/branch shape for plain Git repositories, so `but-agentlog` should not grow\na separate plain-Git fallback model unless the shared API proves insufficient.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:13:24.342Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}